docs/git-worktree-rules.md:3:RunForge must follow the same operational discipline it recommends. Agent work should happen in isolated git state, with explicit provenance before and after every task.
docs/git-worktree-rules.md:7:1. One task = one branch/worktree.
docs/git-worktree-rules.md:8:   - Create a dedicated branch for each agent task.
docs/git-worktree-rules.md:9:   - Prefer a separate worktree for non-trivial work, especially when another task is already in progress.
docs/git-worktree-rules.md:13:   - Tiny read-only inspections are fine. Edits, generated artifacts, test updates, and commits need a task branch.
docs/git-worktree-rules.md:20:   - Treat pre-existing dirty files as user-owned unless the task explicitly includes them.
docs/git-worktree-rules.md:41:   - Do not remove a task worktree while its branch, PR, review, or handoff is still active.
docs/git-worktree-rules.md:42:   - After merge or explicit confirmation, remove the worktree and delete the task branch if appropriate.
docs/git-worktree-rules.md:44:## Starting a new agent task
docs/git-worktree-rules.md:52:git worktree add -b codex/RUNFORGE-TASK-ID ../RunForge-worktrees/runforge-task-id HEAD
docs/git-worktree-rules.md:53:cd ../RunForge-worktrees/runforge-task-id
docs/git-worktree-rules.md:57:Replace `RUNFORGE-TASK-ID` with the task name. If the main worktree is dirty, still create the task worktree from the recorded base commit or from `HEAD`, then leave the dirty main worktree untouched.
docs/git-worktree-rules.md:59:## Handing off a task
docs/git-worktree-rules.md:69:Also run the task-appropriate checks, usually `pnpm dogfood` for RunForge changes. If a commit exists, include:
docs/ROADMAP.md:1:# Agent OS / Task Factory Roadmap
docs/ROADMAP.md:5:RunForge / Factory is an Agent OS: a portable task execution factory.
docs/ROADMAP.md:7:It lets a person or another agent submit a meaningful task, then routes it through a controlled execution loop:
docs/ROADMAP.md:10:task
docs/ROADMAP.md:11:-> clarification or execute-as-is
docs/ROADMAP.md:12:-> plan
docs/ROADMAP.md:13:-> decomposition
docs/ROADMAP.md:15:-> isolated sandbox/runtime execution
docs/ROADMAP.md:16:-> logs and artifacts
docs/ROADMAP.md:17:-> checks and review
docs/ROADMAP.md:18:-> human decision
docs/ROADMAP.md:22:The product is not the internal artifact machinery. The product is reliable end-to-end task execution with enough isolation, evidence, verification, and owner control that a human can safely decide what happens next.
docs/ROADMAP.md:28:Secondary users are other agents that need to submit tasks into the factory and receive structured outcomes instead of vague chat summaries.
docs/ROADMAP.md:30:## System Layers
docs/ROADMAP.md:33:   Accept a task and select the mode: clarify, execute-as-is, or plan-first.
docs/ROADMAP.md:36:   Break large tasks into small isolated subtasks with clear inputs, outputs, constraints, and verification.
docs/ROADMAP.md:42:   Run CLI agents, models, shell tools, integrations, and external providers against scoped subtasks.
docs/ROADMAP.md:45:   Run build, typecheck, tests, lint, CI, safety checks, and task-specific review.
docs/ROADMAP.md:48:   Collect results, compress context, detect conflicts, expose missing evidence, and identify gaps between subtasks.
docs/ROADMAP.md:55:The first practical value is one real end-to-end task run: the system accepts a meaningful task, plans it, decomposes it into 2-5 isolated subtasks, runs them in controlled environments, gathers artifacts, verifies the result, and returns an owner-ready report.
docs/ROADMAP.md:59:The only next milestone is `TASK-RUN-1: First End-to-End Agent OS Task`.
docs/ROADMAP.md:61:`TASK-RUN-1` must:
docs/ROADMAP.md:63:- take one real task;
docs/ROADMAP.md:64:- accept it through task intake;
docs/ROADMAP.md:65:- build a plan;
docs/ROADMAP.md:66:- split it into 2-5 subtasks;
docs/ROADMAP.md:67:- execute subtasks in isolated environments;
docs/ROADMAP.md:68:- collect logs and artifacts;
docs/ROADMAP.md:72:No other milestone should be started before `TASK-RUN-1` proves the loop.
docs/ROADMAP.md:85:These are not the product highway. They are the safety/evidence substrate for Agent OS and should be used only when they help complete end-to-end task execution.
docs/ROADMAP.md:87:## Frozen Until TASK-RUN-1
docs/ROADMAP.md:93:- New safety layers without direct connection to task execution.
docs/ROADMAP.md:94:- Internal artifact work that does not make `TASK-RUN-1` more executable, verifiable, or decision-ready.
docs/ROADMAP.md:98:Before every new task, answer:
docs/ROADMAP.md:104:5. What will we not do in this task?
docs/ROADMAP.md:106:If these answers are missing or weak, do not start the task.
docs/ROADMAP.md:110:The project is drifting when the main output is a new internal viewer, archive, schema, handoff shape, safety layer, or lifecycle report that does not help a task move from intake to verified result to human decision.
docs/ROADMAP.md:112:The project is on course when a real task can enter the factory, be decomposed, run in isolated execution contexts, produce evidence, pass or fail checks honestly, and return a short owner-ready decision report.
docs/CURRENT_STATE.md:5:RunForge is currently a local, deterministic, artifact-first engineering harness. It can collect evidence, run bounded checks, classify failures, produce proposal/readiness packets, render packet views, record operator decisions, and preserve handoff/archive evidence. It is not yet a complete Agent OS / Task Factory because it has not proven one end-to-end task run.
